column2: 5MR - What is the primary foundational principle of the five-man rotation in man down defense?
column3: What is the primary foundational principle of the five-man rotation in man down defense? Derived from: “the first foundation of our five man rotation, man to man, man down defense is the fact that we wanna have our players be able to play the ball straight up. If a player on the offensive team has the ball, we want one of our defensive players to be responsible solely for that player.”

column2: 5MR - What occurs when the ball is passed in the five-man rotation defense?
column3: What occurs when the ball is passed in the five-man rotation defense? Derived from: “Now once we have that, when the ball moves, a new player will become the ball. And everyone else's responsibilities are going to change as the ball swings around the perimeter of the field.”

column2: 5MR - What is the first step in executing the five-man rotation defense?
column3: What is the first step in executing the five-man rotation defense? Derived from: “the first thing we have to do is understand all of the different positions so that then we can understand how each player is going to move in relation to the offense, moving the ball and moving themselves.”

column2: 5MR - What is the primary responsibility of the defender designated as “ball”?
column3: What is the primary responsibility of the defender designated as “ball”? Derived from: “the player who is ball is only responsible for the ball to be able to defend any kind of dodges. They wanna have their stick in front. They wanna try to knock down passes.”

column2: 5MR - Besides marking their assigned offensive player, what additional responsibility do the adja...
column3: Besides marking their assigned offensive player, what additional responsibility do the adjacent defenders have? Derived from: “The other thing that they are responsible for is filling the skip lanes through to the other players. So D1 is responsible for guarding the skip lane through to A3, …”

column2: 5MR - What is the primary role of the defenders designated as “twos” in this rotation?
column3: What is the primary role of the defenders designated as “twos” in this rotation? Derived from: “Now the final responsibility that we have is called A2, … they are responsible for two separate players. So DM one and D2 are our twos.”

column2: 5MR - How do the responsibilities of a “two” defender change as the ball moves?
column3: How do the responsibilities of a “two” defender change as the ball moves? Derived from: “Now as the ball moves depending on the direction, the players they are responsible for may actually change, or they're actually just going to be only responsible for one rather than 2.”

column2: 5MR - When an offensive player cuts to the crease, what is expected of the defender already cover...
column3: When an offensive player cuts to the crease, what is expected of the defender already covering that area? Derived from: “…if those players cut to the middle of the field, they wanna stay with those players… they'll have to communicate who will take A2 if he cuts to the crease…”

column2: 5MR - What is the key action required when the ball changes hands in the rotation?
column3: What is the key action required when the ball changes hands in the rotation? Derived from: “as the ball swings around the perimeter of the field, all of their responsibilities are going to change.”

column2: 5MR - During a carry in the five-man rotation, what is the primary consideration for defenders?
column3: During a carry in the five-man rotation, what is the primary consideration for defenders? Derived from: “if it's a carry, we're gonna maintain our positions and make sure that we are available to fill the roles that were already in.”

column2: 5MR - What is the benefit of rotating a defender from one position to cover an offensive cut inst...
column3: What is the benefit of rotating a defender from one position to cover an offensive cut instead of using an adjacent defender? Derived from: “instead of having D3 cover this cut and become the adjacent, we are actually just gonna have d M1 rotate up so that D3 and D1 can now cover M1, A3 and A2 on the backside.”

column2: 5MR - What is the main difference in defensive positioning between a pass and a carry in the five...
column3: What is the main difference in defensive positioning between a pass and a carry in the five-man rotation? Derived from: “So if it's a pass, we're gonna rotate. If it's a carry, we're gonna maintain our positions…”

column2: 5MR - How does the defense adjust when an offensive player pops off the crease during the rotation?
column3: How does the defense adjust when an offensive player pops off the crease during the rotation? Derived from: “if M3 pops off of the crease here the m one's gonna show to it, and rotate…”

column2: 5MR - In a four-man top wheel, what is the focus of defensive adjustment for players stepping off...
column3: In a four-man top wheel, what is the focus of defensive adjustment for players stepping off the crease? Derived from: “we really wanna notice is how does pen play the players who step off of the crease behind the carry, and how do they play players who are cutting to the crease from the 2 position…”

column2: 5MR - What cue should alert an adjacent defender to rotate up during a top wheel?
column3: What cue should alert an adjacent defender to rotate up during a top wheel? Derived from: “notice how as the ball swings up, the player in the left position notices the player coming off the crease between him and the ball carrier. He maintains his position and rotates up…”

column2: 5MR - In the five-man rotation, how are cuts to the crease typically handled?
column3: In the five-man rotation, how are cuts to the crease typically handled? Derived from: “they're gonna play it like a true five man rotation where the player in the two position is going to stay with the cut and then end up on the opposite side of the field as a two.”

column2: 5MR - When only five perimeter players are available, what is the defensive strategy?
column3: When only five perimeter players are available, what is the defensive strategy? Derived from: “…if there are only 5 perimeter players… we are basically gonna have everyone spider in on the backside.”

column2: 5MR - According to the strategy, why might playing the ball at X be considered less favorable?
column3: According to the strategy, why might playing the ball at X be considered less favorable? Derived from: “I like to play the ball at X because I think that having a player sit back there … is something where we're gonna give up a bunch of goals…and waiting by the pipes because that's much more of a zone principle.”

column2: 5MR - Which of the following is NOT one of the key components when defending the ball in the five...
column3: Which of the following is NOT one of the key components when defending the ball in the five-man rotation? Derived from: “when a player is playing the ball… we wanna break down at the edge of dangerous space… and if there is a possibility of getting in the hands… we definitely wanna throw our check out…”

column2: 5MR - Why is communication critical when a defender locks off a specific zone on the field?
column3: Why is communication critical when a defender locks off a specific zone on the field? Derived from: “in the event that you are locking off a specific location on the field, you need to make sure that you communicate and announce the players who are leaving your zone so that the other zones know to pick up the player who is leaving your zone.”
